{{2010<U+2013>11 Ivy League men's basketball standings}}
The '''2010<U+2013>11 Harvard Crimson men's basketball team''' represented [[Harvard University]] in the [[Ivy League]] athletic conference during the [[2010<U+2013>11 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The team played its home games in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] at the [[Lavietes Pavilion]], which has a capacity of 2,195.  The team was led by fourth-year [[head coach]] [[Tommy Amaker]]. By earning a share of the [[2010<U+2013>11 Ivy League men's basketball season]] title, the team became the first men's basketball Ivy League champion in school history.<ref name=HtP7tsIt/> This was the 100th season for Harvard basketball.<ref name=HBSFIT>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/04/sports/ncaabasketball/04harvard.html|title=Harvard Basketball Seeks First Ivy Title|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-03|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=May, Peter}}</ref>

After the annual 14-game [[round robin]] home & home schedule, Harvard and [[2010<U+2013>11 Princeton Tigers men's basketball team|Princeton]] tied as co-champion, resulting in a [[one-game playoff]] to determine the league's automatic bid to the [[2011 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]]. After losing, the team earned an automatic bid to the [[2011 National Invitation Tournament]], where they lost in the first round.

The seniorless team was [[captain (sports)|captian]]ed by Keith Wright and Oliver McNally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/series/basketball-10-11/article/2010/11/11/basketball-supp-wright-111210/|title=Finding Mister Wright |accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2010-11-11|work=[[Harvard Crimson]]|author=Walsh, Timothy J.}}</ref>  Wright, a junior, was a unanimous All-Ivy first team selection and named League Player of the Year.  Sophomores Kyle Casey and Brandyn Curry were named All-Ivy second team and sophomore Christian Webster was an honorable mention.  The team established a new school record for single-season wins and by going undefeated at home set a record for home wins.

==Preseason==
The team was coming off a [[2009<U+2013>10 Harvard Crimson men's basketball team|2009<U+2013>10 season]] during which it set a school record for wins (21), non-conference wins (11), home wins (11), and road/neutral wins (10).<ref name=ANFFJA>{{cite web|url=http://www.gocrimson.com/sports/mbkb/2009-10/releases/100310_Amaker_Jobe_Finalist|title=Amaker Named Finalist For Jobe Award|accessdate=2010-03-31|date=2010-03-10|publisher=Harvard University}}</ref>  However, the team lost its star [[Jeremy Lin]] to the [[National Basketball Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2010/news/07/21/warriors.lin.ap/index.html|title=Warriors sign undrafted free agent Jeremy Lin|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2010-07-22|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref>  The team entered the season not having participated in the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] since the [[1946 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1946 Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/tournament/history?team1Id=6128|title=NCAA Basketball Tournament History|accessdate=2011-03-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  It also entered the season as the only member school not to have won at least one Ivy League men's basketball championship since the league was formed during the [[1956<U+2013>57 NCAA University Division men's basketball season|1956<U+2013>57 season]].<ref name=HtP7tsIt/>  Of the 34 men's and women's sports in which Harvard competes, this was the only sport that they had never won a championship.  They had only finished in second three times in the past and only one of those was outright.<ref name=HBSFIT/>

Most preseason publications predicted [[2010<U+2013>11 Princeton Tigers men's basketball team|Princeton]] would finish in first place and Harvard would finish in second place, although the ''[[Sporting News]]'' projected that {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Cornell Big Red|school=Cornell University|title=Cornell}} would finish in first followed by Princeton and Harvard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/releases/Mens_Basketball_Abound_with_Preseason_Honors|title=Ivy League Men's Basketball Abound with Preseason Honors Entering the 2010<U+2013>11 Season|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2010-10-15|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com}}</ref> Breaking a three-year streak by [[Cornell Big Red men's basketball|Cornell]], the Ivy League media poll selected Princeton as the top team with twelve first place votes, Harvard second with four first place votes and Cornell third with one first place vote.<ref name=ILMBAwPHEt2S>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/releases/Mens_Basketball_Abound_with_Preseason_Honors|title=Ivy League Men's Basketball Abound with Preseason Honors Entering the 2010<U+2013>11 Season|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2010-10-15|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com}}</ref> It was the first Princeton team to be the preseason selection since the {{cbb link|2004|sex=men|team=Princeton Tigers|school=Princeton University|title=2004<U+2013>05 Princeton team}}.<ref name=ILMBAwPHEt2S/>

==Season==
During the season, the team lost to its only ranked opponent, #4 [[2010<U+2013>11 Connecticut Huskies men's basketball team|Connecticut]] (December 22),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=303560041|title=Kemba Walker scores 20 for 9th straight game as UConn routs Harvard|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2010-12-22|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref> but defeated power conference opponents [[2010-11 Boston College Eagles men's basketball team|Boston College]] (January 5) of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] and [[2010<U+2013>11 Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball team|Colorado]] (November 28) of the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310050103|title=Harvard 78, Boston College 69|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2011-01-05|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=303320108|title=Harvard rides second-half surge past Colorado|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2010-11-28|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref>  The Colorado victory was the team's first ever against a Big 12 opponent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2010/11/29/mbball-colorado-recap-112910/|title=Harvard Men<U+2019>s Basketball Notches First Win Over Big 12 School: Crimson easily handles Colorado, 82<U+2013>66, at Lavietes Pavilion|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2010-11-29|work=[[Harvard Crimson]]|author=Kessler, Martin}}</ref>  In addition to defeating Boston College, the team defeated other cross-town rivals {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Boston Terriers|school=Boston University|title=Boston University}} (December 11) and {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=MIT Engineers|school=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|title=MIT}} (December 31).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=303450108|title=Christian Webster, Harvard top BU to stay perfect at home|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2010-12-11|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=303650108|title=Laurent Rivard, Keith Wright power Harvard to victory vs. MIT|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2010-12-31|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref>  The team also lost to Amaker's former team (as a coach), [[2010<U+2013>11 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]] (December 4).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=303380130|title=Stu Douglass rallies Michigan past Harvard|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2010-12-04|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref> The Harvard gameplan involved [[fast break]]s initiated by its defensive and an inside-outside game.<ref name=HPmiawgfIt>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/basketball/ncaa/03/11/harvard.princeton/|title=Harvard, Princeton meet in a winner-take-all game for Ivy title|accessdate=2011-03-14|date=2011-03-11|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Friedman, Dick}}</ref> Although Harvard never appeared in the [[2010<U+2013>11 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings]], for a few weeks during the season they received a vote in the [[AP Poll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/rankings/_/poll/1/week/12|title=2011 NCAA Men's Basketball Rankings <U+2013> AP Top 25 Week 12 (Jan. 24)|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2011-01-24|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/rankings/_/poll/1/week/13|title=2011 NCAA Men's Basketball Rankings <U+2013> AP Top 25 Week 13 (Jan. 31)|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2011-01-31|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/rankings/_/poll/1/week/16|title=2011 NCAA Men's Basketball Rankings <U+2013> AP Top 25 Week 16 (Feb. 21)|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2011-02-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> 

As the season wound down, there was much ado in the press about a possible Harvard Ivy League championship.<ref name=HBSFIT/><ref name=PaHKP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/26/sports/ncaabasketball/26hoops.html|title=Princeton and Harvard Keep Pace|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-02-25|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=HaPWSUIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/05/sports/ncaabasketball/05hoops.html|title=Harvard and Princeton Win, Setting Up Ivy Showdown|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-04|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  The most recent Harvard team to be in contention for a championship entering the final weekend was the 1984 team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequad.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/04/a-harvard-sweep-dont-remind-me/|title=A Harvard Sweep? Don<U+2019>t Remind Me|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-04|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Plutnicki, Ken}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1984/3/2/its-the-biggest-weekend-of-the/|title=It's the Biggest Weekend Of the Year Cagers Face Cornell In Quest of Ivy Title|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=1984-03-02|work=[[Harvard Crimson]]|author=Zucker, Jeffrey A.}}</ref> On March 5, Harvard clinched a share of the league championship for the first time since the Ivy League was formed.<ref name=HtP7tsIt>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310640108|title=Harvard tops Princeton 79<U+2013>67 to share Ivy title|accessdate=2011-03-06|date=2011-03-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> By defeating [[2010<U+2013>11 Princeton Tigers men's basketball team|Princeton]] at home on March 5 and earning a split of the season series, they clinched at least a share of the [[2010<U+2013>11 Ivy League men's basketball season]] Championship with a 12<U+2013>2 conference record. Princeton fell to 11<U+2013>2 with one conference game remaining to force a one-game playoff for the conferences automatic bid to the [[2011 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref name=HtP7tsIt/> Harvard finished the season a perfect 14<U+2013>0 at home,<ref name=HtP7tsIt/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/06/sports/ncaabasketball/06ivy.html|title=Harvard Has Piece of Title but Wants the Rest of It|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=May, Peter}}</ref> which surpassed the prior season's record of eleven home wins.<ref name=ANFFJA/> Harvard will enter the [[2010<U+2013>11 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]] with a 17-game home streak (10th longest in the country).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/weeklyreleases/2010-11_MBB_Final_Release.pdf|title=2010-11 Highlights|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com|page=5}}</ref> Harvard's 12 conference game wins was also a school record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/weeklyreleases/2010-11_MBB_Final_Release.pdf|title=2010-11 Highlights|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com|page=4}}</ref> On March 7, Harvard received a vote in both the AP Poll and the [[Coaches' Poll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/rankings/_/year/2011/week/18/seasontype/2|title=2011 NCAA Men's Basketball Rankings <U+2013> Week 18 (Mar. 7)|accessdate=2011-03-08|date=2011-03-07|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

==Postseason==
On March 8, Princeton defeated Penn to force a one-game playoff at the [[Payne Whitney Gymnasium]] at [[Yale University]] in [[New Haven, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310670219|title=Princeton tops Penn, sets up one-game playoff with Harvard|accessdate=2011-03-09|date=2011-03-08|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/releases/2011_Mens_Basketball_Playoff|title=2011 Men's Basketball Playoff Information|accessdate=2011-03-12|date=2011-03-11|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/sports/ncaabasketball/09hoops.html|title=Princeton Forces a Playoff for the Ivy<U+2019>s N.C.A.A. Bid|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-08|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Princeton won the playoff by a 63<U+2013>62 margin.<ref name=PKHoljteNb>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310710163|title=Princeton KO's Harvard on last-second jumper to earn NCAA bid|accessdate=2011-03-12|date=2011-03-12|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/sports/ncaabasketball/13ivy.html|title=Princeton Pauses but Still Beats Buzzer on Way to N.C.A.A. Bid|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-12|author=Pennington, Bill|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  However, many thought Harvard had a chance to make the tournament in spite of the loss as an at-large team.<ref name=HPmiawgfIt/><ref name=LPT>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/03/11/sports-bkc-two-bid-ivies_8351619.html|title=Let's Play Two: Ivies hope to put 2nd team in NCAA|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-11|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Golen, Jimmy}}</ref> Four of Harvard's regular season losses were to postseason contenders, and [[2009-10 Cornell Big Red men's basketball team|Cornell]] represented the conference well the year before.<ref name=LPT/> Entering selection Sunday (March 13), Harvard ranked 35th in the [[Ratings Percentage Index]] (RPI).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realtimerpi.com/rpi_Men.html|title=Men's Basketball <U+2013> Team RPIs (2010<U+2013>2011)|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5x9uOEsts|accessdate=2011-03-13|date=2011-03-13|archivedate=2011-03-13|publisher=RealTimeRPI.Com.}}</ref> However, Harvard was not selected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=6212994|title=2011 NCAA tournament selections|accessdate=2011-03-13|date=2011-03-13|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Unfortunately, neither of Harvard's quality wins (against Colorado and Boston College) helped them because both teams were left out of the NCAA tournament and relegated to number one seed status in the NIT tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/sports/ncaabasketball/14nit.html|title=Playoff Defeat Sends Harvard to the N.I.T.|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-13|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> It was the Ivy League's first NIT invitation since the [[2003 National Invitation Tournament|2003]] when Brown participated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/weeklyreleases/2010-11_MBB_Final_Release.pdf|title=2010-11 Highlights|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com|page=1}}</ref> As a regular season champion not invited to the NCAA tournament, they were an automatic selection for the [[2011 National Invitation Tournament]], where they were seeded #6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=6214252|title=Colorado, Virginia Tech lead NIT field|accessdate=2011-03-14|date=2011-03-13|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On March 15, Harvard was defeated by {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Oklahoma State Cowboys|school=Oklahoma State University|title=Oklahoma State}} by a 71<U+2013>54 margin in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310740197|title=Oklahoma State routs Harvard in NIT opener|accessdate=2011-03-16|date=2011-03-15|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  The final record of 23<U+2013>7 established a school record for number of wins, surpassing the prior season's total of 21.<ref name=ANFFJA/><ref name=PaHKP/>  Harvard finished the season ranked 40th nationally by the ''Collegiate Basketball News'' RPI, CollegeRPI.com RPI and NCAA RPI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/weeklyreleases/2010-11_MBB_Final_Release.pdf|title=2010-11 Highlights|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com|page=9}}</ref> The team finished second in the nation in [[free throw percentage]] (80.8%), led by Oliver McNally who was 2nd as an individual with a 92.6% and Christian Webster who was 12th with an 89.4%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/sports/mbkb/2010-11/weeklyreleases/2010-11_MBB_Final_Release.pdf|title=2010-11 Highlights|publisher=Ivyleaguesports.com|page=13}}</ref>  Harvard had no seniors on the team and was expected to be a contender again the following season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequad.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/live-updates-selection-sunday/|title=Selection Sunday Analysis|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-13|author=Hillesland, Zach|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

